00:00:26.290 --> 00:00:29.410
ANDREW LO: These are the
financial highlights of Lehman

00:00:29.410 --> 00:00:31.780
Brothers as of the end of 2007.

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:33.430
Now, you can get more
recent highlights

00:00:33.430 --> 00:00:35.380
from looking at
their SEC filings,

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:38.170
their 10-K and 10-Qs
which are accounting

00:00:38.170 --> 00:00:41.060
reports that they provide to
the SEC on a quarterly basis.

00:00:41.060 --> 00:00:44.710
But I just thought we'd take a
look at the annual financials

00:00:44.710 --> 00:00:46.860
of this business.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:52.840
At the end of 2007, the net
revenues for Lehman Brothers

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:56.100
was $19 billion.

00:00:56.100 --> 00:01:01.560
This is a firm that earned $19
billion in revenues in 2007.

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:04.709
We're not talking about
a small little shop here.

00:01:04.709 --> 00:01:07.170
This is a major
financial institution.

00:01:07.170 --> 00:01:10.770
And if you look at their
profits, their net income,

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:14.670
$4 billion of net
income in 2007.

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:20.240
And 2007 was not a great
year, so $4 billion of income

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:22.900
is a pretty impressive number.

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:28.500
And if you look at their
long-term capital, the capital

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:32.140
base, we're looking
at $145 billion.

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:37.760
And if you take a look at
their assets under management,

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:46.456
the assets under management,
in billions, is $282 billion

00:01:46.456 --> 00:01:49.830
of assets under management.

00:01:49.830 --> 00:01:53.780
Now, at the end of
2007, would anybody

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:57.530
have forecasted that
a company like this

00:01:57.530 --> 00:01:59.660
could be gone nine months later?

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:04.370
Gone-- I mean, just obliterated.

00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:09.139
28,500 employees, so we're
talking about major disruption

00:02:09.139 --> 00:02:11.090
to the New York workforce.

00:02:11.090 --> 00:02:13.400
A number of people are going
to be looking for jobs.

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:15.140
Now, a number of
jobs are going to be

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:19.120
created as a consequence
of these dislocations.

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:21.310
I'll come to that in a minute.

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:24.760
But this is an
extraordinary set of events.

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:30.300
And one key to what's
going on and why

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:34.760
this might have happened
is this number right here,

00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:37.330
the net leverage ratio.

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:40.060
That net leverage
ratio tells you

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:46.240
something about how much
exposure Lehman Brothers had

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:52.240
relative to how much capital
they're actually managing.

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:55.120
And let me give you an example
of what I mean by that.

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:56.630
And I'm going to give you a
personal example that we're

00:02:56.630 --> 00:02:57.546
going to come back to.

00:02:57.546 --> 00:02:59.260
We talked about
mortgages last time,

00:02:59.260 --> 00:03:01.510
and I told you all that
you now have the power

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:03.710
to compute mortgage payments.

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:05.950
Well, you know that a
mortgage is a loan, right?

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:07.450
You're borrowing
money from the bank

00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:10.950
to buy this beautiful home
that you want to live in.

00:03:10.950 --> 00:03:13.080
Does anybody know how
much money you typically

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.350
have to put down
when you buy a home?

00:03:16.350 --> 00:03:16.850
Yeah.

00:03:16.850 --> 00:03:17.460
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:19.001
ANDREW LO: 20% is
the typical number,

00:03:19.001 --> 00:03:21.820
although in recent years,
it's much less than that.

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:27.000
For example, when I first
bought my home way back in 1988,

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.480
my first home, when I
moved here to Boston,

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:34.070
I actually only
had to put 5% down

00:03:34.070 --> 00:03:39.710
because I was able to get a
jumbo loan and, in addition,

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:43.610
purchase mortgage insurance
so that the bank was

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:48.350
willing to lend me quite a bit
more than they usually would.

00:03:48.350 --> 00:03:50.570
Now, let's take the 20%
down as the standard number

00:03:50.570 --> 00:03:54.320
because that is absolutely
industry standard.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:59.137
If you put down 20% for,
let's say, a $500,000 home--

00:03:59.137 --> 00:04:01.220
which in the Boston area
is a little starter home,

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:02.430
I'm afraid--

00:04:02.430 --> 00:04:07.390
a half a million dollar
home you put down $100,000.

00:04:07.390 --> 00:04:10.570
And the bank lends you $400,000.

00:04:10.570 --> 00:04:15.130
The value of your total assets
is, of course, 500,000, right?

00:04:15.130 --> 00:04:18.310
You've got 100,000 of your own
money, 400,000 of the bank's

00:04:18.310 --> 00:04:21.010
money, and with that 500,000,
you give it to the other party

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:22.040
to buy the home.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:27.070
And now you are the happy
owners of a $500,000 home.

00:04:27.070 --> 00:04:30.250
What kind of leverage ratio do
you have in that circumstance?

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:32.567
Anybody calculate that quickly?

00:04:32.567 --> 00:04:34.555
AUDIENCE: It's 4 to 1?

00:04:34.555 --> 00:04:37.390
ANDREW LO: Close, but no cigar.

00:04:37.390 --> 00:04:38.830
5 to 1, right?

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:42.340
5 to 1 in the sense that you
have five times leverage.

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:43.930
Your total exposure is 500.

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:45.070
You've got 100.

00:04:45.070 --> 00:04:46.600
It's 5 to 1.

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:49.150
Now, what does that
mean, 5 to 1 leverage?

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:50.750
That sounds scary.

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:54.460
That sounds like you
are really levered up.

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:59.110
Well, it's only scary if
the value of the assets

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:02.230
swings around a lot.

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:04.720
For example, let's do a
simple back-of-the-envelope

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:06.290
calculation.

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:11.590
Suppose house
prices fall by 10%.

00:05:11.590 --> 00:05:13.320
That's only 10%, right?

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:14.380
That's not a huge number.

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:17.530
It's significant,
but it's not huge.

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:20.980
What's the return
on your investment?

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:22.780
How much have you
invested in the home?

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:23.530
AUDIENCE: 100,000.

00:05:23.530 --> 00:05:25.390
ANDREW LO: $100,000.

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:28.750
If the value of the
home falls by 10%,

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:31.340
how much has the value
of your assets fallen by?

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:33.010
50,000, right?

00:05:33.010 --> 00:05:37.355
Of that 50,000, how
much does the bank lose?

00:05:37.355 --> 00:05:37.980
AUDIENCE: None.

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:40.450
ANDREW LO: None, right,
because they've lent you money,

00:05:40.450 --> 00:05:42.140
and they expect
you to pay it back.

00:05:42.140 --> 00:05:43.360
They're not equity holders.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:45.970
They're not looking to
take on any downside risk.

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:48.410
They just want their
money back with interest.

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:51.400
So the bank doesn't
care what the value is.

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:55.540
They still expect you to pay
back the $400,000 that they

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:57.200
lent you with interest.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:02.330
So that $50,000
loss, it's all yours.

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:08.820
And you've put down 100,000,
and you've lost 50--

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:10.980
half of your assets
just got wiped out

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:16.560
with only a 10% move in
the value of the home.

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:18.990
Now, instead of putting 20%
down as a standard, what

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:23.510
if you did what I did,
which is you put down 5%?

00:06:23.510 --> 00:06:29.490
So 5% of $500,000
is $25,000, right?

00:06:29.490 --> 00:06:32.850
The bank lends you $475,000.

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:34.650
So this is not a
conforming loan.

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:38.340
You've got to buy insurance,
and it's subprime,

00:06:38.340 --> 00:06:39.900
so on and so forth.

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:44.050
5% is your investment, $25,000.

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:49.920
Now, suppose housing
prices go down by 10%.

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:53.098
What's the return
on your capital?

00:06:53.098 --> 00:06:54.550
AUDIENCE: Negative.

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:57.530
ANDREW LO: Well, you've
lost everything, right?

00:06:57.530 --> 00:07:02.840
The $50,000 loss is still
there, but you only put in 25.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:06.830
So you've now lost all of your
capital, and on top of that,

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:11.180
you're in the hole
for another 25.

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:16.550
So you've actually lost not
only all of your wealth,

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:19.440
but actually, you've
lost more than all of it.

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:23.960
You've lost minus 100% of your
wealth or your total return.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:28.470
Your net return is minus 200%.

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:32.130
So, if you're a major
financial institution,

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:39.140
and you're leveraged 16 to 1,
and the value of that portfolio

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:46.730
declines by 10% or 20%, you
can go through capital very,

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:47.960
very quickly.

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:49.570
Now let's do a back
of the envelope.

00:07:49.570 --> 00:07:51.430
The amount of capital
that they have-- let's

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:53.620
go up and take a look at this.

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:57.520
The amount of capital that
Lehman had is something like--

00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:03.120
total long-term capital
$145 billion, OK?

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:10.040
If you leverage that 16 to 1,
and then you ask the question,

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:13.030
with that leverage
amount of capital,

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:18.020
if it drops by, I
don't know, 10%, 5%,

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:22.330
7% of that total
asset base, you can

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:25.120
see how you can go through
$145 billion of capital

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:28.500
pretty quickly with leverage.

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:31.210
Now, you might ask, why on
earth would anybody do this?

00:08:31.210 --> 00:08:34.289
Why would you leverage 16 to 1?

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:38.610
Well, why would anybody
buy a house in New England

00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:40.820
with 5% down?

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:41.809
That's just as crazy.

00:08:41.809 --> 00:08:44.717
What's the leverage
ratio if you put 5% down?

00:08:44.717 --> 00:08:45.855
AUDIENCE: 20 to 1.

00:08:45.855 --> 00:08:47.230
ANDREW LO: 20 to
1, exactly, so I

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:51.852
was a proud leveraged investor
that had 20 to 1 leverage.

00:08:51.852 --> 00:08:52.810
I beat Lehman Brothers.

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:56.440
Why would I do that?

00:08:56.440 --> 00:08:58.270
Is that insane?

00:08:58.270 --> 00:08:59.032
Well, yeah.

00:08:59.032 --> 00:09:01.240
AUDIENCE: So you don't
[? tie ?] up too much capital.

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:02.320
ANDREW LO: Well, yes.

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:04.030
That's a very polite
way of saying it.

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:06.405
Yes, I would tie up too much
capital if I didn't do that.

00:09:06.405 --> 00:09:08.420
The fact is, I didn't
have the capital.

00:09:08.420 --> 00:09:10.920
So thank you for being kind.

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:12.310
But why wasn't it nuts?

00:09:12.310 --> 00:09:13.436
Yeah.

00:09:13.436 --> 00:09:16.459
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:16.459 --> 00:09:17.250
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:20.420
If the value goes
up, then I earn

00:09:20.420 --> 00:09:22.800
that kind of money,
the same kind of money.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:28.340
So if housing prices go up by
10%, then at 20 to 1 leverage,

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:30.410
I look like a hedge
fund manager, right?

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:32.929
Make a ton of money, but
that's not the only reason

00:09:32.929 --> 00:09:34.970
that I'm willing to do
that because you're saying

00:09:34.970 --> 00:09:37.580
that I want to take that risk.

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:39.170
Why would I do that?

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:40.522
Yeah, Michael.

00:09:40.522 --> 00:09:42.230
AUDIENCE: Well, your
risk seems very low.

00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:42.963
ANDREW LO: Why?

00:09:42.963 --> 00:09:44.463
AUDIENCE: Well, in
the past, there's

00:09:44.463 --> 00:09:46.379
nothing to indicate that
prices would go down.

00:09:46.379 --> 00:09:47.210
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:52.130
The risk of 20 to 1
leverage is only a risk

00:09:52.130 --> 00:09:55.460
if the amount of housing
price fluctuation

00:09:55.460 --> 00:09:58.310
is such that it could
actually wipe me out.

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:01.580
But up until very
recently, housing prices

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:03.590
have done nothing but this.

00:10:03.590 --> 00:10:04.816
They've gone up.

00:10:04.816 --> 00:10:06.440
And not only have
they gone up, they've

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:10.160
gone up in a very smooth
and orderly fashion.

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:13.640
You know, if house prices went
up by 15% a year every year,

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:16.289
you might be thrilled,
but also a bit scared.

00:10:16.289 --> 00:10:17.330
That's not what happened.

00:10:17.330 --> 00:10:19.413
Housing prices have gone
up, maybe, I don't know--

00:10:19.413 --> 00:10:23.580
8%, 10%, 7%, 5%, 6%.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:26.490
It's been relatively smooth.

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:29.610
And so the volatility,
the volatility

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:32.670
of those kinds of
investments were low enough

00:10:32.670 --> 00:10:35.130
that the leverage
didn't scare me at all.

00:10:35.130 --> 00:10:37.320
And in fact, I
didn't lose money.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:40.410
I held that house for
about five or six years

00:10:40.410 --> 00:10:44.080
and bought another
one, and it was fine.

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:46.680
It was fine because
that kind of leverage

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:49.730
is not a problem as
long as the volatility

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:53.980
of the overall investment
wasn't out of hand.

00:10:53.980 --> 00:10:56.830
What happened over the
last two or three years

00:10:56.830 --> 00:10:59.540
is that the volatility
has gotten out of hand.

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:01.780
And we're going to talk
about that Wednesday

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:03.040
at that pro seminar.

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:05.620
I'm going to give you a concrete
illustration not only of how

00:11:05.620 --> 00:11:09.640
it got out of hand, but
how financial engineering

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:12.220
and the design of
derivative securities

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:16.330
to expand the housing market and
provide people with these loans

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:19.120
exacerbated the problem
on the downside.

00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:21.310
But of course, the
purpose of it was

00:11:21.310 --> 00:11:22.750
to help people on the upside.

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:24.850
It's exactly looking
at the investments

00:11:24.850 --> 00:11:29.210
going up and thinking that,
gee, they could never come down.

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:29.878
Yeah, question.

00:11:29.878 --> 00:11:32.253
AUDIENCE: What about the fact
that at the end of the day,

00:11:32.253 --> 00:11:33.862
you can live in your house?

00:11:33.862 --> 00:11:35.854
And the total valuation
of your house,

00:11:35.854 --> 00:11:38.350
if it goes down $100,000,
it's still a [INAUDIBLE]..

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:39.221
ANDREW LO: Right.

00:11:39.221 --> 00:11:41.220
AUDIENCE: So you only
have to deal with the mark

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:42.560
to market [? up and down. ?]

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:44.560
ANDREW LO: That's a
very important point.

00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:46.190
The mark to market.

00:11:46.190 --> 00:11:48.450
What does mark to market mean?

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:49.119
Anybody know?

00:11:49.119 --> 00:11:50.910
We've never used that
term in class so far.

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:51.582
Yeah.

00:11:51.582 --> 00:11:54.294
AUDIENCE: It's something that
book value gets [? matched ?]

00:11:54.294 --> 00:11:55.650
[? together with ?] reality.

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:56.650
ANDREW LO: That's right.

00:11:56.650 --> 00:12:00.000
When something that may
have a book value gets

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.810
marked to a reality check
in terms of market price.

00:12:04.810 --> 00:12:06.660
So for example,
the first lecture,

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:09.450
where I auctioned off
that little tiny box

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:11.400
that you had no idea
what was in there,

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:13.350
it had no market
value beforehand,

00:12:13.350 --> 00:12:15.720
at least not to any of you.

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:17.730
But we marked it to market.

00:12:17.730 --> 00:12:21.100
We marked it to
market at 45 bucks.

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:23.780
And so it established
a market price.

00:12:23.780 --> 00:12:28.300
Now, the question is, who cares
what the value of the house is?

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:30.280
You're living in it,
you're enjoying it,

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:32.039
so what's the big deal?

00:12:32.039 --> 00:12:32.830
Well, that's right.

00:12:32.830 --> 00:12:36.490
It's not a big deal if you
enjoy living in the house,

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:39.610
and you can afford to pay
the mortgage, and you're OK.

00:12:39.610 --> 00:12:43.490
And millions of homeowners
are exactly in that situation.

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:45.440
So we can't forget that.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:48.190
That the subprime mortgage
has enabled literally

00:12:48.190 --> 00:12:51.250
millions of homeowners
to become homeowners

00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:53.700
who never could have.

00:12:53.700 --> 00:12:57.480
But what if there's a problem
in terms of interest rates going

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:00.180
up and your mortgage
payment going up

00:13:00.180 --> 00:13:03.270
because you ended up
getting a very low teaser

00:13:03.270 --> 00:13:05.250
rate for your mortgage?

00:13:05.250 --> 00:13:06.840
You've got an
adjustable rate mortgage

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:08.880
because they said, gee,
you could buy this house

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:10.650
with virtually no money down.

00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:13.560
And you've got
plenty of resources

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:16.500
to be able to pay for it because
your payment is only $300

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:17.280
a month.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:19.560
And then, a year later,
that mortgage payment

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:20.940
is $1,000 a month.

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:22.710
Then it's a real problem.

00:13:22.710 --> 00:13:25.110
OK, then you've got a decision.

00:13:25.110 --> 00:13:27.750
The decision is, are
you going to keep

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:32.310
paying all of your income
and have a hard time making

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:37.060
ends meet for a house
that you'll never

00:13:37.060 --> 00:13:38.230
get the money back?

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:41.410
It's literally taking
your money and burning it

00:13:41.410 --> 00:13:43.450
because you've lost your equity.

00:13:43.450 --> 00:13:45.520
And you've lost so much
more beyond your equity

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:47.260
that in order to
make money you'd

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:49.330
have to hold onto the
house for 20 years,

00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:52.940
and you can't afford
the house anyway.

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:54.436
Do you do that?

00:13:54.436 --> 00:13:56.060
Or do you put the
key in the front door

00:13:56.060 --> 00:13:59.150
and move out and say, you know
what, bank, it's all yours.

00:13:59.150 --> 00:14:00.990
I'm moving on.

00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:02.740
That's what's happened
across the country.

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:05.280
It's the fact that people
can't afford these mortgages

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:08.016
because they got in
at low teaser rates,

00:14:08.016 --> 00:14:10.140
and now the rates have come
up because the interest

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:11.490
rates have been going up.

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:14.430
Now, something very significant
is going to happen tomorrow.

00:14:14.430 --> 00:14:17.100
Tomorrow, the Fed
is almost surely

00:14:17.100 --> 00:14:19.350
going to cut rates
because they want

00:14:19.350 --> 00:14:23.580
to reduce the pressure
on the system for exactly

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:24.510
these kinds of issues.

00:14:24.510 --> 00:14:28.320
They want to reduce the
kind of default rates.

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:31.020
And by keeping
interest rates low,

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:33.600
they actually are going
to be able to encourage

00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:36.300
liquidity and reduce
the kind of pressure

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:37.400
that we've been seeing.

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:39.329
Yeah, question.

00:14:39.329 --> 00:14:40.704
AUDIENCE: I was
going to ask what

00:14:40.704 --> 00:14:44.220
happens if you put your 5%
down, and the value of the house

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:48.415
goes down, say, 25%,
it's been only a year.

00:14:48.415 --> 00:14:50.531
You feel like you're not
going to get-- it's never

00:14:50.531 --> 00:14:51.447
going to come back up.

00:14:51.447 --> 00:14:55.050
Can you literally just go to
the bank and say it's yours?

00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:57.660
ANDREW LO: Well, that depends
on what you signed when you got

00:14:57.660 --> 00:14:59.010
your mortgage from the bank.

00:14:59.010 --> 00:15:03.090
Most mortgage contracts are
known as non-recourse loans,

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:06.806
meaning that they've got
your house as collateral,

00:15:06.806 --> 00:15:07.930
but that's all they've got.

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:09.640
They don't have
your firstborn, they

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:13.129
don't have your pinky finger.

00:15:13.129 --> 00:15:15.170
And depending on where
you borrow, in some cases,

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:17.440
you may have to give that up.

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:20.470
But no, the fact of the
matter is the most they can do

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:23.530
is take your house
away and sell it.

00:15:23.530 --> 00:15:27.340
And a lot of homeowners are
saying, great, it's all yours.

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:29.022
I'm moving out of
Stockton, California.

00:15:29.022 --> 00:15:29.980
I don't need the house.

00:15:29.980 --> 00:15:31.870
I don't need to have
these mortgage payments

00:15:31.870 --> 00:15:34.670
where I'm throwing in
good money after bad.

00:15:34.670 --> 00:15:36.460
That's their perspective.

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:38.410
AUDIENCE: What about
your credit score?

00:15:38.410 --> 00:15:40.618
ANDREW LO: Yes, so your
credit score will go to hell.

00:15:40.618 --> 00:15:41.520
So you wait.

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:43.450
So you'll wait five
years or seven years,

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:46.360
and then you'll be back again.

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:49.120
There's a finite
limit on how long

00:15:49.120 --> 00:15:51.910
they can keep those
kind of credit scores.

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:56.080
And beyond a certain point,
you will have a clean record.

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:58.931
But even with that
bad credit score--

00:15:58.931 --> 00:16:01.180
I mean, don't forget, that's
how the subprime mortgage

00:16:01.180 --> 00:16:02.110
market got created.

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:03.341
You saw the TV ads, right?

00:16:03.341 --> 00:16:04.840
Doesn't matter if
you're in default,

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:06.310
doesn't matter if
you have no credit,

00:16:06.310 --> 00:16:07.935
doesn't matter if
you don't have a job,

00:16:07.935 --> 00:16:10.110
we'll still give you a loan.

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:13.420
Now, that's not true today,
or not as true today,

00:16:13.420 --> 00:16:15.820
but at some point when
the market recovers,

00:16:15.820 --> 00:16:17.680
we're going to see
that come back again.

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:21.645
And so you will be
able to borrow again.

00:16:21.645 --> 00:16:23.285
Yeah.

00:16:23.285 --> 00:16:25.493
AUDIENCE: Given that the
interest rates are now going

00:16:25.493 --> 00:16:27.810
up, does that mean
the [INAUDIBLE]----

00:16:27.810 --> 00:16:30.370
ANDREW LO: Going down.

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:35.457
AUDIENCE: Despite the fact that
the financial cut [INAUDIBLE],,

00:16:35.457 --> 00:16:39.086
the actual interest rate
that homeowners are paying

00:16:39.086 --> 00:16:39.900
hasn't changed.

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:40.140
ANDREW LO: Right.

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:42.431
AUDIENCE: So does that mean
that those with good credit

00:16:42.431 --> 00:16:44.840
are effectively subsidizing
those with bad credit?

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:47.530
ANDREW LO: Well, yes and no.

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:49.810
I mean, I think that
the subsidization

00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:53.500
that you're talking about really
happens very, very indirectly.

00:16:53.500 --> 00:16:56.740
The fact that there are
large numbers of defaults

00:16:56.740 --> 00:16:59.980
ultimately may mean that it's
harder to get a subprime loan.

00:16:59.980 --> 00:17:01.630
So the folks that
are actually good

00:17:01.630 --> 00:17:05.710
credits, but don't meet the
prime borrowing rate criteria,

00:17:05.710 --> 00:17:07.970
yes, they will suffer.

00:17:07.970 --> 00:17:11.660
But at equilibrium-- by
equilibrium I mean when supply

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:13.430
equals demand--

00:17:13.430 --> 00:17:15.710
the price is the
price is the price.

00:17:15.710 --> 00:17:20.030
So it depends on what kind
of a borrower you are,

00:17:20.030 --> 00:17:22.310
but whatever type
of borrower you

00:17:22.310 --> 00:17:26.210
are, if you can signal that
that's the type you are,

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:29.090
you will be able to get that
appropriate kind of credit.

00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:31.220
All right, so in
that sense, it's

00:17:31.220 --> 00:17:33.530
not as if taxpayers
are footing the bill

00:17:33.530 --> 00:17:36.590
for the particular interest
rate shifts that are going on.

00:17:36.590 --> 00:17:39.050
Taxpayers may end up
footing the bill for what

00:17:39.050 --> 00:17:41.450
happened with Bear Stearns,
what happened with Fannie

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:42.740
Mae and Freddie Mac.

00:17:42.740 --> 00:17:45.910
And that's one of the reasons
why, over the weekend,

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:48.380
when the Fed was approached
by Lehman Brothers and said,

00:17:48.380 --> 00:17:50.480
hey, you've got to
help us out here,

00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:52.280
the Fed said, you know what?

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:53.210
We're done with that.

00:17:53.210 --> 00:17:56.870
You know, sorry, but we can't
ask the American taxpayer

00:17:56.870 --> 00:17:58.400
to foot this bill either.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:01.190
Otherwise there's going
to be tremendous backlash.

00:18:01.190 --> 00:18:03.410
And so when Lehman
Brothers was left

00:18:03.410 --> 00:18:06.050
without backing
from the Fed, they

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:09.289
went to a number of private
organizations like Barclays.

00:18:09.289 --> 00:18:11.330
Barclays said that they
would be willing to do it

00:18:11.330 --> 00:18:13.850
if the Fed was able to
provide some kind of backstop.

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:15.766
The Fed was not willing
to provide a backstop,

00:18:15.766 --> 00:18:17.690
so Barclays said
thanks, but no thanks.

00:18:17.690 --> 00:18:21.410
And at that point, Lehman said,
we have no choice because we

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:26.090
cannot close a sale within a
matter of 24 to 48 hours from

00:18:26.090 --> 00:18:27.230
this point on.

00:18:27.230 --> 00:18:29.030
And we've got some
notes coming up.

00:18:29.030 --> 00:18:32.820
We've got to do something,
so they filed for Chapter 11.

00:18:32.820 --> 00:18:33.590
Yeah.

00:18:33.590 --> 00:18:35.030
AUDIENCE: If they cut the
rates [? as far as ?] they do,

00:18:35.030 --> 00:18:36.470
what's the negative part?

00:18:36.470 --> 00:18:37.430
Inflation?

00:18:37.430 --> 00:18:38.340
ANDREW LO: Yes.

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:40.490
We're actually going
to talk about that

00:18:40.490 --> 00:18:42.860
in this next segment--

00:18:42.860 --> 00:18:43.760
inflation.

00:18:43.760 --> 00:18:47.210
If the Fed cuts
rates, one could argue

00:18:47.210 --> 00:18:49.430
that the reason we're
in the mess that we are

00:18:49.430 --> 00:18:51.860
is because the Fed
had kept the Fed funds

00:18:51.860 --> 00:18:55.820
rate so low for so long
that even after the stock

00:18:55.820 --> 00:18:58.310
market crashed with the
internet bubble bursting,

00:18:58.310 --> 00:19:01.790
the housing market
continued on with its bubble

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:03.830
because it was still
so cheap to borrow.

00:19:03.830 --> 00:19:06.131
And I'm sure I've
mentioned before

00:19:06.131 --> 00:19:08.630
that when I was an assistant
professor at the Wharton School

00:19:08.630 --> 00:19:11.550
back in 1986 looking
to buy a house,

00:19:11.550 --> 00:19:15.070
the 30-year fixed was at 18%.

00:19:15.070 --> 00:19:17.170
18% for a 30-year
fixed mortgage.

00:19:17.170 --> 00:19:20.180
I didn't do it because I
couldn't afford it at the time,

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:22.570
but think about
that versus today.

00:19:22.570 --> 00:19:27.970
Mortgage rates are maybe at
a recent high of 6%, 7%, 8%.

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:32.320
That's not bad, relative
to historical standards.

00:19:32.320 --> 00:19:35.430
OK, so yes, I mean, I
think that's the concern

00:19:35.430 --> 00:19:37.810
that if we keep
interest rates too low,

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:39.580
that's going to
encourage inflation.

00:19:39.580 --> 00:19:41.530
And inflation will
have its own costs.

00:19:41.530 --> 00:19:45.760
Anybody who's from any
Latin American country

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:49.184
will know the ghost of inflation
is tremendously frightening.

00:19:49.184 --> 00:19:51.100
And we don't want to let
that get out of hand.

00:19:51.100 --> 00:19:53.290
If you remember
back to the 1970s,

00:19:53.290 --> 00:19:56.650
we had some inflation in the
US that was a real problem.

00:19:56.650 --> 00:20:00.000
So we're going to talk about
that in just a couple minutes.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:00.970
Any other?

00:20:00.970 --> 00:20:01.737
Yes.

00:20:01.737 --> 00:20:05.216
AUDIENCE: I mean, is one
thing to do [INAUDIBLE]..

00:20:05.216 --> 00:20:07.204
You said that when
the market comes back,

00:20:07.204 --> 00:20:10.190
we will still have
another bubble.

00:20:10.190 --> 00:20:11.550
ANDREW LO: Absolutely, yes.

00:20:11.550 --> 00:20:13.650
AUDIENCE: And do you
think this is reasonable?

00:20:13.650 --> 00:20:15.840
ANDREW LO: Do I think
it's reasonable?

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:18.810
You're not allowed to ask
that question to an economist.

00:20:18.810 --> 00:20:22.680
Or rather, an economist is
not allowed to answer that.

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:26.580
Reasonable is relative.

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:29.704
And there are moral
and ethical overtones

00:20:29.704 --> 00:20:31.620
that economists don't
like to get involved in.

00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:33.400
It's human nature.

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:38.017
Is it human to suffer
from fear and greed?

00:20:38.017 --> 00:20:39.600
Well, yes, and I
don't think I'm going

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:42.210
to change that any
time soon, nor are you

00:20:42.210 --> 00:20:44.590
going to be able to
change that any time soon.

00:20:44.590 --> 00:20:47.070
So that's one of
the reasons why we

00:20:47.070 --> 00:20:51.140
study finance is to develop an
intellectual and disciplined

00:20:51.140 --> 00:20:52.890
framework for thinking
about these issues.

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:54.840
Because if you
don't, if you don't

00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:57.180
have a framework for
thinking about this,

00:20:57.180 --> 00:21:00.090
then you're left responding
to fear and greed.

00:21:00.090 --> 00:21:05.430
Right now, we are in the
absolute grips of fear.

00:21:05.430 --> 00:21:07.320
Those of you who aren't
in financial markets,

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:09.210
if you read the papers,
my guess is you'll

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:11.690
start getting scared anyway.

00:21:11.690 --> 00:21:13.230
And if you're in
financial markets,

00:21:13.230 --> 00:21:15.960
I promise you this
is the scariest time

00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:21.660
that we've been in, including
August of '98, October '87,

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:25.050
'94, 2001.

00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:28.440
All of the kind of periods
of market dislocation

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:32.102
is trumped by what's been going
on over the last few weeks.

00:21:32.102 --> 00:21:34.560
And it's exciting from the
point of view of being a finance

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:36.930
student because you actually
have the opportunity

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:40.160
to understand and do
something about this.

00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:43.020
But it requires a certain
discipline to do that.

00:21:43.020 --> 00:21:44.110
Yeah, Ingrid.

00:21:44.110 --> 00:21:46.610
AUDIENCE: What does it exactly
mean that Lehman Brothers are

00:21:46.610 --> 00:21:47.110
bankrupt?

00:21:47.110 --> 00:21:51.264
Because everybody, I guess
it's not a written one,

00:21:51.264 --> 00:21:54.510
but if I have some
money deposited there,

00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:58.410
will they give it back to
me because I am a liability?

00:21:58.410 --> 00:22:01.330
ANDREW LO: Well, that's
exactly the problem.

00:22:01.330 --> 00:22:03.470
The answer is I don't know.

00:22:03.470 --> 00:22:05.970
And that's one of the reasons
why there is this dislocation.

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:07.710
Nobody knows
because nobody knows

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:11.310
how large the losses could be.

00:22:11.310 --> 00:22:13.159
And part of the thing
is that the losses

00:22:13.159 --> 00:22:14.950
at Lehman and other
financial institutions,

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:15.991
including Merrill Lynch--

00:22:15.991 --> 00:22:18.720
Merrill Lynch in some ways has
bigger exposure than Lehman.

00:22:18.720 --> 00:22:20.220
The difference is
that Merrill Lynch

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:21.690
has other sources
of revenue that

00:22:21.690 --> 00:22:25.440
are able to let it get
through this situation a bit

00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:27.330
more gracefully.

00:22:27.330 --> 00:22:29.220
But the problem is we
don't know because we

00:22:29.220 --> 00:22:32.910
don't know how the value
of these large assets

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:34.080
are going to be valued.

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:37.110
If you value them at zero,
then they're in deep trouble.

00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:38.567
And not only are
the shareholders

00:22:38.567 --> 00:22:40.650
going to get wiped out,
but a lot of the creditors

00:22:40.650 --> 00:22:41.850
are going to get wiped out.

00:22:41.850 --> 00:22:44.700
If you value them at
what they're valued now,

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:47.790
well, then there are going to
be some hiccups along the way,

00:22:47.790 --> 00:22:49.710
but a number of
people should get out

00:22:49.710 --> 00:22:53.127
without outrageous losses.

00:22:53.127 --> 00:22:55.626
AUDIENCE: And can't you sort
of declare default, stop paying

00:22:55.626 --> 00:23:02.009
now, until thing get better?

00:23:02.009 --> 00:23:04.300
I'm sort of applying my Latin
American experience here.

00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:05.910
ANDREW LO: Yes, yes.

00:23:05.910 --> 00:23:08.970
I mean that's exactly what
filing for bankruptcy does.

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:12.450
When you file for bankruptcy,
you basically go to the courts

00:23:12.450 --> 00:23:17.670
and say, I cannot
make good on my IOUs.

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:20.200
And I recognize that
this is a problem.

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:24.420
So I'm going to ask the court
to appoint a conservator

00:23:24.420 --> 00:23:29.250
or supervisor to
oversee the disposition

00:23:29.250 --> 00:23:32.130
and dissolution of
my assets in order

00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:36.540
to make an orderly transition
to pay off all of the creditors.

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:39.440
And you know who's last in line?

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:40.009
Shareholders.

00:23:40.009 --> 00:23:40.550
That's right.

00:23:40.550 --> 00:23:42.620
So most people think
the shareholders

00:23:42.620 --> 00:23:44.670
are going to get
nothing, which is

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:47.850
kind of astonishing because
take a look at their closing

00:23:47.850 --> 00:23:49.920
price in 2007.

00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:55.300
The closing price of Lehman
Brothers stock, $62 a share

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:57.280
at the end of 2007.

00:23:57.280 --> 00:24:00.520
Nine months later,
it's worth zero.

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:03.700
Zero, from $62 a share.

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:07.240
That's a huge
destruction of value.

00:24:07.240 --> 00:24:07.990
And you know what?

00:24:07.990 --> 00:24:13.870
Part of that loss in value is
really due to the loss of brand

00:24:13.870 --> 00:24:17.030
and the loss of
business viability.

00:24:17.030 --> 00:24:19.120
It's intangible assets.

00:24:19.120 --> 00:24:22.810
It's not like all of a sudden,
the Lehman investment bankers

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:26.380
and proprietary traders
and asset managers,

00:24:26.380 --> 00:24:29.150
they had brain damage and
they're a lot stupider

00:24:29.150 --> 00:24:30.350
than they used to be.

00:24:30.350 --> 00:24:32.980
They're just as smart, just
as savvy, just as experienced,

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:36.100
just as knowledgeable
as ever were.

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:38.560
The problem is that
because of the magnitude

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:41.710
of their exposures,
there is general concern

00:24:41.710 --> 00:24:43.870
about their viability
as a business.

00:24:43.870 --> 00:24:46.180
