00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:45.070
and annuities and compounding.

00:30:45.070 --> 00:30:48.490
And where we ended with was
this notion of inflation.

00:30:48.490 --> 00:30:51.670
How many of you already know
what inflation is and you've

00:30:51.670 --> 00:30:54.220
talked about it in macro?

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:55.340
OK, some of you.

00:30:55.340 --> 00:30:57.580
So let me go over it briefly.

00:30:57.580 --> 00:31:00.070
And I think you'll see
very quickly exactly

00:31:00.070 --> 00:31:01.900
what the idea is.

00:31:01.900 --> 00:31:06.040
It's really meant to capture
the fact that the purchasing

00:31:06.040 --> 00:31:11.380
power of your money can
vary over time, irrespective

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:14.230
of the time value of money.

00:31:14.230 --> 00:31:16.510
And let me explain it this way--

00:31:16.510 --> 00:31:20.440
at a particular point in
time, let's say time t,

00:31:20.440 --> 00:31:23.230
you've got a certain
amount of wealth, wt.

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:28.330
And the value of the kinds of
things that you like to buy

00:31:28.330 --> 00:31:29.890
is given by an index.

00:31:29.890 --> 00:31:30.580
Call it I sub t.

00:31:30.580 --> 00:31:34.240
So you could think about that
as the price of the basket

00:31:34.240 --> 00:31:36.210
of goods that you enjoy.

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:37.210
OK?

00:31:37.210 --> 00:31:43.510
So this will include consumer
items, food, clothing.

00:31:43.510 --> 00:31:46.610
As well, it may include other
items-- leisure, entertainment,

00:31:46.610 --> 00:31:48.480
and so on.

00:31:48.480 --> 00:31:52.310
And the fact that you have
a certain amount of wealth

00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:55.730
doesn't really tell
you how happy you are.

00:31:55.730 --> 00:31:58.370
It's really how much
you're able to consume.

00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:01.220
How you use that wealth that
tells you how happy you are.

00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:03.470
So economists
really like to focus

00:32:03.470 --> 00:32:07.700
not on total wealth as a measure
of your standard of living,

00:32:07.700 --> 00:32:10.070
but how you are able
to consume that wealth.

00:32:10.070 --> 00:32:12.620
So we're going to come up with
a basket of consumption goods

00:32:12.620 --> 00:32:18.080
and call that price of that
basket, I sub t, all right?

00:32:18.080 --> 00:32:20.360
Now let's move from time
t to a different point

00:32:20.360 --> 00:32:21.740
in time, t plus k.

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:24.440
So k periods from
now, you're going

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:26.600
to have a different
amount of wealth.

00:32:26.600 --> 00:32:28.580
Hopefully bigger.

00:32:28.580 --> 00:32:32.620
And presumably, you're going
to be able to consume more.

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:37.120
Well, that's presuming
that the prices of what you

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:41.220
like to consume don't change.

00:32:41.220 --> 00:32:44.320
But if those prices do
change, then in fact,

00:32:44.320 --> 00:32:48.470
you might not be really
better off in any way.

00:32:48.470 --> 00:32:50.840
And so in order for you
to tell whether or not

00:32:50.840 --> 00:32:53.420
you're better off
or worse off, you

00:32:53.420 --> 00:32:56.790
need to know not only
how much wealth you have,

00:32:56.790 --> 00:32:59.790
but how much that wealth can
buy you in terms of the stuff

00:32:59.790 --> 00:33:01.780
that you like to consume.

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:07.440
So the idea behind inflation
is to measure the purchasing

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:10.500
power of your dollar.

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:14.680
And that's completely different
from time value of money.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:17.550
Time value of money simply
says that people are impatient

00:33:17.550 --> 00:33:20.660
and they prefer money
now to money later.

00:33:20.660 --> 00:33:25.820
But inflation is a comment
about the purchasing

00:33:25.820 --> 00:33:30.080
power of that dollar
now versus later.

00:33:30.080 --> 00:33:31.440
And it can go either way.

00:33:31.440 --> 00:33:35.630
In other words, it's possible
that a dollar next year

00:33:35.630 --> 00:33:39.440
will buy you more
than a dollar today

00:33:39.440 --> 00:33:43.400
because if prices decline, as
they have right now for energy,

00:33:43.400 --> 00:33:44.000
for example.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.340
Energy is below $100 a barrel.

00:33:46.340 --> 00:33:49.290
Just a few months ago,
it was at $130 a barrel.

00:33:49.290 --> 00:33:52.220
So if we had a winter
a few months ago,

00:33:52.220 --> 00:33:55.100
that would have been really bad
because home heating oil would

00:33:55.100 --> 00:33:56.683
have been a lot more
expensive than it

00:33:56.683 --> 00:33:57.890
looks like it's going to be.

00:33:57.890 --> 00:34:00.140
However, it's still going
to be more expensive than it

00:34:00.140 --> 00:34:05.070
was two years ago, when
oil was at $40 a barrel.

00:34:05.070 --> 00:34:06.910
So you need to know
what you're going

00:34:06.910 --> 00:34:09.409
to consume in order to get a
sense of whether you are better

00:34:09.409 --> 00:34:10.174
or worse off.

00:34:10.174 --> 00:34:11.840
And that's what we
measure by this price

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:15.280
index, I of t plus k.

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:17.889
So when you're looking
at your portfolio,

00:34:17.889 --> 00:34:19.270
you might ask the
question what's

00:34:19.270 --> 00:34:21.250
my return on my portfolio.

00:34:21.250 --> 00:34:23.110
And the way you
calculate that return

00:34:23.110 --> 00:34:27.010
is look at your wealth at time
t plus k divided by your wealth

00:34:27.010 --> 00:34:30.540
at time t, subtract 1 from it.

00:34:30.540 --> 00:34:32.670
And that's your return, right?

00:34:32.670 --> 00:34:36.120
That's often called
the nominal return

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:39.510
because it's in
name only, meaning

00:34:39.510 --> 00:34:43.350
it's the actual
number of dollar bills

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:45.120
that your wealth will grow to.

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:47.820
So if you've got
$1,000 this year,

00:34:47.820 --> 00:34:51.719
next year you've got
$1,100, your nominal return

00:34:51.719 --> 00:34:53.610
for your wealth is 10%.

00:34:53.610 --> 00:34:55.739
That's the number
of dollar bills

00:34:55.739 --> 00:34:58.050
you'll have more than
you had this year.

00:34:58.050 --> 00:35:00.240
10% more.

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.500
Now if you want
to know how you're

00:35:02.500 --> 00:35:04.860
doing in terms of your
level of happiness,

00:35:04.860 --> 00:35:07.290
your purchasing power,
your cost of living,

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:09.030
your standard of
living, you've got

00:35:09.030 --> 00:35:13.020
to look at what's going on
with a cost of living increase.

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:16.530
I sub t plus k
divided by I sub t.

00:35:16.530 --> 00:35:23.860
And we can write that as a
fixed growth rate, pi, per year.

00:35:23.860 --> 00:35:26.790
1 plus pi to the k

00:35:26.790 --> 00:35:29.610
So let's suppose that all
the prices of the things

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:32.120
you love and enjoy--

00:35:32.120 --> 00:35:35.650
they go up by 10% as well.

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:37.750
Well, then have
you made any money?

00:35:37.750 --> 00:35:39.400
Have you made any progress?

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:41.890
You've made money, but
you haven't made progress.

00:35:41.890 --> 00:35:46.960
You've made 10% in terms of your
return on your initial $1,000.

00:35:46.960 --> 00:35:52.270
But the stuff that you like
to eat and buy and use--

00:35:52.270 --> 00:35:54.530
that's also gone up by 10%.

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:59.420
So in fact, you can't do any
more consumption next year

00:35:59.420 --> 00:36:01.150
than you could have this year.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:04.030
Because while your wealth went
up by 10%, the cost of living

00:36:04.030 --> 00:36:06.400
went up by 10%.

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:09.070
So from a real perspective--

00:36:09.070 --> 00:36:12.660
real meaning what you
really care about--

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:15.950
you haven't really
made any progress.

00:36:15.950 --> 00:36:19.370
Inflation is a measure of
how much progress we've made.

00:36:19.370 --> 00:36:23.210
And so when you
engage in analysis

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:26.900
of these kinds of
present value problems,

00:36:26.900 --> 00:36:29.810
you've got to ask the
question whether or not

00:36:29.810 --> 00:36:36.320
you're focusing on nominal
returns or real returns, OK?

00:36:36.320 --> 00:36:40.190
And ultimately, as a consumer,
what you all care about

00:36:40.190 --> 00:36:42.570
is real returns.

00:36:42.570 --> 00:36:45.830
You want to know whether you're
getting better off in terms

00:36:45.830 --> 00:36:48.770
of what you can really consume.

00:36:48.770 --> 00:36:51.780
So how do you do that.

00:36:51.780 --> 00:36:55.620
Well, first of all, you
have to change the units.

00:36:55.620 --> 00:36:57.256
Sorry, question?

00:36:57.256 --> 00:36:59.110
