00:37:34.690 --> 00:37:38.050
So here, what I've
done is to define

00:37:38.050 --> 00:37:42.700
a variable called your real
wealth at time t plus k.

00:37:42.700 --> 00:37:45.550
Real meaning this
is what you really

00:37:45.550 --> 00:37:49.060
can do with your money
in terms of consuming.

00:37:49.060 --> 00:37:52.730
What it is is your
nominal wealth divided

00:37:52.730 --> 00:37:56.400
by the rate of inflation.

00:37:56.400 --> 00:37:58.610
So in the case of the
example I gave you,

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:02.150
where your nominal
wealth goes up by 10%

00:38:02.150 --> 00:38:07.440
and your inflation rate
goes up by 10%, when

00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:10.530
you take your nominal
wealth and you divide it

00:38:10.530 --> 00:38:14.430
by that growth rate in
inflation, what do you get?

00:38:17.530 --> 00:38:20.160
You get $1,000.

00:38:20.160 --> 00:38:24.060
In other words, your wealth
hasn't changed in real terms.

00:38:24.060 --> 00:38:24.840
OK?

00:38:24.840 --> 00:38:28.530
So in the example that I gave
you your wealth went up by 10%.

00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:32.470
Your inflation rate
for a year is also 10%.

00:38:32.470 --> 00:38:38.334
So if you divide your
total wealth by that index,

00:38:38.334 --> 00:38:39.750
you're basically
going to get back

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:43.560
to your original amount
of wealth, right?

00:38:43.560 --> 00:38:47.100
So here's the general framework.

00:38:47.100 --> 00:38:51.990
Your real wealth is going to
be your nominal wealth divided

00:38:51.990 --> 00:38:54.350
by the rate of inflation.

00:38:54.350 --> 00:38:55.880
You're dividing by
it because you're

00:38:55.880 --> 00:39:01.460
using, as your units of
comparison, today's consumption

00:39:01.460 --> 00:39:02.816
basket.

00:39:02.816 --> 00:39:05.390
Right?

00:39:05.390 --> 00:39:10.100
So the way you can look at your
real return, which is denoted 1

00:39:10.100 --> 00:39:15.710
plus r real to the k-th power,
your real return over k years

00:39:15.710 --> 00:39:19.520
is equal to the real wealth at
the end of year k years divided

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:20.475
by your wealth today.

00:39:20.475 --> 00:39:22.100
That's your real rate
of return, right?

00:39:22.100 --> 00:39:27.630
Because it's how much real
dollars you have at time k.

00:39:27.630 --> 00:39:32.070
That's just given
by your nominal rate

00:39:32.070 --> 00:39:34.880
of return of your wealth.

00:39:34.880 --> 00:39:38.750
And then divided by
the rate of inflation.

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:40.080
OK?

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:43.200
So this is the
expression that is

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:49.080
the basic relationship between
real and nominal consumption

00:39:49.080 --> 00:39:50.260
goods.

00:39:50.260 --> 00:39:54.480
And then we
approximate this ratio

00:39:54.480 --> 00:39:57.510
with this very, very
simple relationship here.

00:39:57.510 --> 00:40:00.910
The real rate of
return is approximately

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:06.160
equal to the nominal rate of
return minus the inflation

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:07.630
rate-- not divided by anything.

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:09.610
That's the approximation.

00:40:09.610 --> 00:40:11.970
So getting back to my example.

00:40:11.970 --> 00:40:14.920
My example of if you
have a 10% nominal growth

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:20.060
rate for your investment and
you have a 10% inflation rate,

00:40:20.060 --> 00:40:23.570
then in that case,
there's no approximation.

00:40:23.570 --> 00:40:26.720
In fact, your inflation rate,
your real rate of return,

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:28.100
is zero, right?

00:40:28.100 --> 00:40:30.300
10% minus 10% is zero.

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:31.850
Where the approximation
happens is

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:34.080
when you have something
a little bit different.

00:40:34.080 --> 00:40:38.640
For example, suppose the
inflation rate were 10%

00:40:38.640 --> 00:40:41.846
and suppose your nominal
rate of return was 15%.

00:40:41.846 --> 00:40:43.470
According to this
approximation, what's

00:40:43.470 --> 00:40:45.990
your real rate of return?

00:40:45.990 --> 00:40:46.900
5%, right.

00:40:46.900 --> 00:40:56.470
It's not exactly 5% because if
you take 1.15 divided by 1.10,

00:40:56.470 --> 00:40:58.780
it's not exactly 5%.

00:40:58.780 --> 00:41:00.970
But it's approximately
equal to that.

00:41:00.970 --> 00:41:02.980
OK?

00:41:02.980 --> 00:41:07.080
What this says is that you ought
to think, as a consumer, not

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:09.480
just about the
total dollars that's

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:14.040
growing but the purchasing
power of those dollars.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:15.220
OK.

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:19.810
For the purposes of
doing NPV calculations,

00:41:19.810 --> 00:41:23.710
I want to just mention
one rule of thumb that

00:41:23.710 --> 00:41:26.500
will do you in good
stead, no matter what kind

00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:28.870
of calculations you do.

00:41:28.870 --> 00:41:32.050
And that is simply to keep
track of whether you're using

00:41:32.050 --> 00:41:36.880
nominal or real cash flows.

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:41.180
And then to use nominal or
real discount rates to match.

00:41:41.180 --> 00:41:42.910
In other words,
nominal cash flow

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:45.940
should be divided by
nominal discount rates.

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:50.830
And real cash flow should be
denominated by real discount

00:41:50.830 --> 00:41:52.270
rates.

00:41:52.270 --> 00:41:56.020
Most of the cash flows that you
will get in your analysis will

00:41:56.020 --> 00:41:58.411
typically be nominal.

00:41:58.411 --> 00:42:01.210
Nominal meaning that's the
actual number of dollars

00:42:01.210 --> 00:42:03.700
you will see on those dates.

00:42:03.700 --> 00:42:06.370
But occasionally, you
may get a forecast

00:42:06.370 --> 00:42:08.510
that is made in real terms--

00:42:08.510 --> 00:42:11.704
in terms of purchasing power.

00:42:11.704 --> 00:42:13.120
And in that case,
you have to just

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:14.830
be careful to use the
right interest rate when

00:42:14.830 --> 00:42:16.080
you're doing your discounting.

00:42:16.080 --> 00:42:18.890
You have to take into
account inflation.

00:42:18.890 --> 00:42:22.590
Nominal gets discounted by
nominal, real gets discounted

00:42:22.590 --> 00:42:23.090
by real.

00:42:23.090 --> 00:42:27.359
That's all you have
to remember, OK?

