00:51:37.950 --> 00:51:40.710
but they aren't
typically the same ones.

00:51:40.710 --> 00:51:43.800
Whereas I would argue
that Microsoft and Google

00:51:43.800 --> 00:51:48.120
are traded every minute
of the trading day.

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:50.790
So typically, bonds do
trade, but they don't

00:51:50.790 --> 00:51:54.310
trade on organized exchanges.

00:51:54.310 --> 00:51:56.860
And that makes them less liquid.

00:51:56.860 --> 00:52:03.400
Even the very, very safest
and most liquid bonds

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:08.170
do not trade as frequently
as equities and futures.

00:52:08.170 --> 00:52:11.424
So the liquidity characteristics
can be very, very different

00:52:11.424 --> 00:52:12.340
for these instruments.

00:52:12.340 --> 00:52:15.820
And these complex securities,
like collateralized debt

00:52:15.820 --> 00:52:17.890
obligations, mortgage
backed securities--

00:52:17.890 --> 00:52:21.400
they trade even less frequently
because they are highly complex

00:52:21.400 --> 00:52:24.490
and it's not easy to figure
out what their prices are

00:52:24.490 --> 00:52:28.350
from minute to minute every day.

00:52:28.350 --> 00:52:31.030
Now the fixed income
market participants

00:52:31.030 --> 00:52:35.350
that we're going to be focused
on fall into three groups--

00:52:35.350 --> 00:52:40.260
issuers, intermediaries,
and investors.

00:52:40.260 --> 00:52:45.300
Issuers, of course, are the
end users of these instruments.

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:48.030
They include everything
from governments

00:52:48.030 --> 00:52:51.010
down to foreign institutions.

00:52:51.010 --> 00:52:54.840
These are the folks that issue
pieces of paper that are IOUs

00:52:54.840 --> 00:52:57.000
and they get cash
in return for that

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:59.320
to finance their operations.

00:52:59.320 --> 00:53:03.240
And in return, they
pay interest, OK?

00:53:03.240 --> 00:53:05.830
The investors, of
course, are the folks

00:53:05.830 --> 00:53:11.320
that are buying the paper or
essentially providing loans.

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:13.090
So every once in a
while, when I go out

00:53:13.090 --> 00:53:15.970
with my colleagues for
lunch in the finance group,

00:53:15.970 --> 00:53:19.060
one of my colleagues will
say, can I sell you a bond,

00:53:19.060 --> 00:53:20.650
I didn't go to the
cash machine today,

00:53:20.650 --> 00:53:23.440
and I need you to help
me finance my lunch.

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:28.720
These are how finance
professors speak, unfortunately.

00:53:28.720 --> 00:53:32.830
The idea about
buying somebody bond

00:53:32.830 --> 00:53:36.070
is you're lending
them money, right?

00:53:36.070 --> 00:53:38.870
So instead of saying could
you let me $5, we have to say,

00:53:38.870 --> 00:53:41.650
well, I'm going to issue a
bond, can you buy my bond.

00:53:44.640 --> 00:53:47.380
The investors are the
ones that are loaning

00:53:47.380 --> 00:53:50.260
the money to the issuers.

00:53:50.260 --> 00:53:50.920
OK?

00:53:50.920 --> 00:53:53.510
And these include, as I said,
governments, pension funds,

00:53:53.510 --> 00:53:58.300
insurance companies, banks,
hedge funds, and so on.

00:53:58.300 --> 00:54:02.590
In the middle of all of
this are the intermediaries.

00:54:02.590 --> 00:54:05.630
Primary dealers, other
kinds of dealers,

00:54:05.630 --> 00:54:09.490
investment banks, the
credit rating agencies,

00:54:09.490 --> 00:54:10.840
the credit enhancers.

00:54:10.840 --> 00:54:12.520
What do I mean by
credit enhancers?

00:54:12.520 --> 00:54:17.350
Folks that help credit
markets by providing insurance

00:54:17.350 --> 00:54:20.470
to the credit, like
private mortgage insurance.

00:54:20.470 --> 00:54:21.910
And liquidity enhancers.

00:54:21.910 --> 00:54:23.380
These are the
counter-parties that

00:54:23.380 --> 00:54:25.660
try to bring buyers
and sellers together

00:54:25.660 --> 00:54:28.930
to increase the
liquidity of the markets.

00:54:28.930 --> 00:54:33.530
The dislocation has been going
on in the intermediary sector

00:54:33.530 --> 00:54:37.250
and of course, the issuers
are having some difficulties

00:54:37.250 --> 00:54:39.290
now because they're going
to have to make good

00:54:39.290 --> 00:54:40.610
on these kind of claims.

00:54:40.610 --> 00:54:44.240
And the people that are
going to be hurt ultimately

00:54:44.240 --> 00:54:47.630
will be the investors who are
holding pieces of paper that

00:54:47.630 --> 00:54:50.070
may not be worth as
much as possible.

00:54:50.070 --> 00:54:52.670
And so the efforts now
at trying to shore up

00:54:52.670 --> 00:54:56.540
the finances of Fannie Mae and
Freddie Mac, Lehman, Merrill,

00:54:56.540 --> 00:54:59.060
and all of these
other institutions

00:54:59.060 --> 00:55:01.540
is really aimed at
trying to help out

00:55:01.540 --> 00:55:05.240
a combination of the
intermediaries and the issuers.

00:55:05.240 --> 00:55:07.850
Because if you don't help out
this group, then what happens

00:55:07.850 --> 00:55:11.120
is that this group
is going to get hit.

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:14.430
So Lehman Brothers, for
example, is an intermediary.

00:55:14.430 --> 00:55:16.212
They are one of
the biggest dealers

00:55:16.212 --> 00:55:17.420
in these kinds of securities.

00:55:17.420 --> 00:55:20.330
Merrill Lynch is also one
of the biggest dealers

00:55:20.330 --> 00:55:21.530
in these kind of securities.

00:55:21.530 --> 00:55:26.930
As dealers, they end up taking
exposure on their own books.

00:55:26.930 --> 00:55:30.050
That's not a great
idea in general

00:55:30.050 --> 00:55:33.710
because the best
of all worlds is

00:55:33.710 --> 00:55:36.624
you're the toll collector
that's collecting tolls

00:55:36.624 --> 00:55:38.790
for traffic going back and
forth and back and forth.

00:55:38.790 --> 00:55:40.630
You don't take any risk.

00:55:40.630 --> 00:55:43.870
But if not everybody
wants to go back and forth

00:55:43.870 --> 00:55:45.910
and back and forth and
back and forth, you

00:55:45.910 --> 00:55:49.690
might stand ready to do
one side of the business

00:55:49.690 --> 00:55:52.880
and let other folks do the
other side of the business.

00:55:52.880 --> 00:55:56.170
But if you're not careful
in laying off your exposure

00:55:56.170 --> 00:55:58.810
you can end up getting
hurt pretty badly.

00:55:58.810 --> 00:56:02.050
An example of this that happened
in equity markets in 1987

00:56:02.050 --> 00:56:04.010
was when the stock
market crashed.

00:56:04.010 --> 00:56:07.750
That was a very serious
event on October 19, 1987,

00:56:07.750 --> 00:56:11.560
where in one single day,
the US stock market lost

00:56:11.560 --> 00:56:13.990
approximately 20% of its value.

00:56:13.990 --> 00:56:15.550
In one day.

00:56:15.550 --> 00:56:17.680
Now, that's a
serious dislocation.

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:19.480
We're going to talk
about that this Friday

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:20.920
when we run this trading game.

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:23.770
I'm going to have all of you
engage in trading over a very

00:56:23.770 --> 00:56:24.770
short period of time.

00:56:24.770 --> 00:56:27.130
So you're going to be under
tremendous pressure as well.

00:56:27.130 --> 00:56:29.920
You tell me how easy it
is to think on the fly.

00:56:29.920 --> 00:56:32.680
What happened that morning
of October 19, 1987,

00:56:32.680 --> 00:56:34.942
is that the specialists,
the dealers, who

00:56:34.942 --> 00:56:36.400
are supposed to be
making markets--

00:56:36.400 --> 00:56:38.140
their job is to
buy when everybody

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:42.120
wants to sell and to sell
when everybody wants to buy.

00:56:42.120 --> 00:56:44.670
They got it there in
the morning at 9:30

00:56:44.670 --> 00:56:49.120
and were overwhelmed with
everybody wanting to sell.

00:56:49.120 --> 00:56:50.530
So they ended up buying--

00:56:50.530 --> 00:56:51.950
the specialists.

00:56:51.950 --> 00:56:52.720
And they bought.

00:56:52.720 --> 00:56:56.360
And as they bought, what
happened to the price?

00:56:56.360 --> 00:56:57.170
Kept going down.

00:56:57.170 --> 00:56:58.753
That means more
people wanted to sell.

00:56:58.753 --> 00:56:59.630
So they kept buying.

00:56:59.630 --> 00:57:01.770
And as they bought,
what happened?

00:57:01.770 --> 00:57:03.200
Price kept going down.

00:57:03.200 --> 00:57:04.820
And it kept going
down all the way.

00:57:04.820 --> 00:57:07.460
So the stuff that they
bought in the morning

00:57:07.460 --> 00:57:11.390
was worth 20% less
in the afternoon.

00:57:11.390 --> 00:57:15.710
And these market makers
also used leverage.

00:57:15.710 --> 00:57:18.770
So many of their capital
bases were wiped out

00:57:18.770 --> 00:57:22.340
by that 20% decline in a
day because they were just

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:24.620
doing their job.

00:57:24.620 --> 00:57:27.630
In fact, there was a story--

00:57:27.630 --> 00:57:30.830
the floor of the New York Stock
Exchange was literally packed.

00:57:30.830 --> 00:57:33.980
I mean, it was tighter
than a Tokyo subway train

00:57:33.980 --> 00:57:35.510
during rush hour, OK?

00:57:35.510 --> 00:57:36.180
It was packed.

00:57:36.180 --> 00:57:40.880
I mean literally, you were
elbow to elbow against others.

00:57:40.880 --> 00:57:43.060
Unfortunately, one
of the market makers

00:57:43.060 --> 00:57:47.890
had a heart attack
around 1 or 2 o'clock.

00:57:47.890 --> 00:57:53.470
And he wasn't able
to fall to the ground

00:57:53.470 --> 00:57:56.980
until the market closed at
four because he was propped up

00:57:56.980 --> 00:58:01.480
by everybody else desperate
to try to transact.

00:58:01.480 --> 00:58:03.550
And he died.

00:58:03.550 --> 00:58:10.780
And somebody who was near
him said, you know, look,

00:58:10.780 --> 00:58:12.061
I knew the guy was in trouble.

00:58:12.061 --> 00:58:13.310
But what was I supposed to do.

00:58:13.310 --> 00:58:17.530
I was 100,000 shares long and
I had to unload my portfolio.

00:58:17.530 --> 00:58:19.000
I mean, they were trading.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:22.540
That's how desperate
it was on that day.

00:58:22.540 --> 00:58:28.420
So this kind of intermediation
can be extraordinarily high

00:58:28.420 --> 00:58:29.140
pressure.

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:32.920
And when you're engaged in
an unwinding of portfolios,

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:34.310
dislocation can occur.

00:58:34.310 --> 00:58:36.760
So we're seeing that
right now play out.

00:58:36.760 --> 00:58:39.296
And it's a little different
because we're dealing

00:58:39.296 --> 00:58:40.420
with fixed income security.

00:58:40.420 --> 00:58:42.940
So I'm going to come
back and talk about that.

00:58:42.940 --> 00:58:43.660
OK.

00:58:43.660 --> 00:58:45.130
That's the background
to what we're

00:58:45.130 --> 00:58:47.980
going to study-- these fixed
income markets and fixed income

00:58:47.980 --> 00:58:48.654
instruments.

00:58:48.654 --> 00:58:51.070
I'm going to ask you to read
Brealey and Myers so that you

00:58:51.070 --> 00:58:52.945
can get up to speed on
institutional details.

00:58:52.945 --> 00:58:54.520
And there are quite
a few, so I would

00:58:54.520 --> 00:58:56.530
urge you to please
do that reading

00:58:56.530 --> 00:58:59.320
and make sure that you
understand the basic terms

00:58:59.320 --> 00:59:00.970
of these markets.

00:59:00.970 --> 00:59:04.600
What I want to talk about,
though, is the framework.

00:59:04.600 --> 00:59:08.050
I want to give you a framework
for thinking about evaluating

00:59:08.050 --> 00:59:09.065
fixed income securities.

00:59:09.065 --> 00:59:10.690
And really, as I
said, it's a framework

00:59:10.690 --> 00:59:11.606
that you already know.

00:59:11.606 --> 00:59:13.330
You already have
that in your mind.

00:59:13.330 --> 00:59:16.900
I've already changed the way you
think about financial markets

00:59:16.900 --> 00:59:20.860
by asking you to focus on cash
flows and timing and the time

00:59:20.860 --> 00:59:21.590
value of money.

00:59:21.590 --> 00:59:24.220
That's all you need in order to
value fixed income securities.

00:59:24.220 --> 00:59:26.680
The rest is just
institutional detail,

00:59:26.680 --> 00:59:29.470
which, while very
important, is not something

00:59:29.470 --> 00:59:31.570
that we need to
worry about in class.

00:59:31.570 --> 00:59:34.240
But I'll leave to
you to focus on.

00:59:34.240 --> 00:59:37.620
So let me give you an example
of valuation and how to do it.

00:59:37.620 --> 00:59:38.920
It will be a very short one.

00:59:38.920 --> 00:59:41.090
You all know how to do this.

00:59:41.090 --> 00:59:45.630
We've got a sequence of cash
flows for a particular security

00:59:45.630 --> 00:59:47.750
that I'm going to call a bond.

00:59:47.750 --> 00:59:50.720
And in particular, I'm going
to call this a coupon bond.

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:53.300
Now with a coupon
bond, there are

00:59:53.300 --> 00:59:54.780
two things you need to know.

00:59:54.780 --> 00:59:57.020
You need to know
what the coupon is

00:59:57.020 --> 01:00:00.020
and you need to know
the maturity-- how

01:00:00.020 --> 01:00:02.450
many dates that it pays off.

01:00:02.450 --> 01:00:04.910
One of the institutional
details that you'll need to know

01:00:04.910 --> 01:00:09.500
is that coupon bonds
typically pay semiannually.

01:00:09.500 --> 01:00:12.530
Some coupon bonds can pay
quarterly, but most of them,

01:00:12.530 --> 01:00:14.960
as a matter of convention,
pay semiannually.

01:00:14.960 --> 01:00:16.670
But that changes
depending on the market.

01:00:16.670 --> 01:00:18.878
So you'll need to learn a
little bit about those kind

01:00:18.878 --> 01:00:20.246
of conventions.

01:00:20.246 --> 01:00:21.620
I'm not going to
worry about that

01:00:21.620 --> 01:00:23.078
and I'm going to
abstract from that

01:00:23.078 --> 01:00:27.590
and simply say that here's a
three year coupon bond that

01:00:27.590 --> 01:00:31.740
has a principal of $1,000.

01:00:31.740 --> 01:00:35.510
That's the typical
principal or face value

01:00:35.510 --> 01:00:37.400
that a bond comes with.

01:00:37.400 --> 01:00:40.220
So this piece of
paper is an IOU.

01:00:40.220 --> 01:00:46.700
And it says, I owe you $1,000
at the end of three years, OK?

01:00:46.700 --> 01:00:49.730
But I'm not going to
pay you just $1,000

01:00:49.730 --> 01:00:51.110
at the end of three years.

01:00:51.110 --> 01:00:57.330
I'm going to pay you $50 every
year for those three years.

01:00:57.330 --> 01:01:02.910
So the coupon is a 5% coupon.

01:01:02.910 --> 01:01:07.770
So when you hear of a coupon
bond that's a 5% three year

01:01:07.770 --> 01:01:11.830
bond, that term
that I just uttered

01:01:11.830 --> 01:01:17.050
means that it pays off $1,000
at the end of three years.

01:01:17.050 --> 01:01:21.609
And in the interim, it pays
off $50 a year as it's coupons.

01:01:21.609 --> 01:01:22.900
Why is it called a coupon bond?

01:01:22.900 --> 01:01:25.840
In the old days, the bond
was actually a piece of paper

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:28.900
and on the bottom of
it were little coupons.

01:01:28.900 --> 01:01:31.630
And you'd clip the
coupons and mail them in.

01:01:31.630 --> 01:01:33.880
And once a year when you
mail them in, or twice a year

01:01:33.880 --> 01:01:37.521
when you mail them
in, you get back $50.

01:01:37.521 --> 01:01:38.020
OK?

01:01:38.020 --> 01:01:40.330
Nowadays, it's all
done electronically.

01:01:40.330 --> 01:01:44.220
So first thing you do in order
to value of the cash flow--

01:01:44.220 --> 01:01:46.060
draw a time line, OK?

01:01:46.060 --> 01:01:48.460
We're here sitting at
zero, that's today.

01:01:48.460 --> 01:01:50.140
And you've got
three years to go.

01:01:50.140 --> 01:01:52.240
One year, two year, three years.

01:01:52.240 --> 01:01:55.500
At the end of three years,
you get paid your principal--

01:01:55.500 --> 01:01:57.250
$1,000--

01:01:57.250 --> 01:01:58.860
plus the coupon.

01:01:58.860 --> 01:02:01.460
There are three coupons
for three years.

01:02:01.460 --> 01:02:07.170
And so at the end of this
bond, when the bond matures,

01:02:07.170 --> 01:02:09.660
you get paid $1,050.

01:02:09.660 --> 01:02:13.770
And then $50, $50, and
here we are at date zero.

01:02:13.770 --> 01:02:17.040
Question-- what is this worth?

01:02:17.040 --> 01:02:18.435
Yeah?

01:02:18.435 --> 01:02:20.760
AUDIENCE: It depends
on the interest rate.

01:02:20.760 --> 01:02:21.500
ANDREW LO: Right.

01:02:21.500 --> 01:02:25.648
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] interest
rates are exactly 5%, so it's

01:02:25.648 --> 01:02:27.762
worth just $1000, the same.

01:02:27.762 --> 01:02:28.470
ANDREW LO: Right.

01:02:28.470 --> 01:02:32.700
If the interest rate is 5%,
it's worth $1,000 today.

01:02:32.700 --> 01:02:33.810
That's par.

01:02:33.810 --> 01:02:37.107
But if the interest rate
is worth less than that--

01:02:37.107 --> 01:02:40.320
AUDIENCE: Worth
more [INAUDIBLE]..

01:02:40.320 --> 01:02:41.490
ANDREW LO: Right, exactly.

01:02:41.490 --> 01:02:45.970
So in general, how do you figure
out the price of this thing?

01:02:45.970 --> 01:02:47.561
Yeah.

01:02:47.561 --> 01:02:51.489
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
vice versa [INAUDIBLE]??

01:02:56.865 --> 01:02:59.490
ANDREW LO: Well no, I was asking
a somewhat different question,

01:02:59.490 --> 01:03:01.948
which is, how do I figure out
the market value of this bond

01:03:01.948 --> 01:03:03.405
today times 0.

01:03:03.405 --> 01:03:05.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:05.830 --> 01:03:09.110
ANDREW LO: Yeah, compute
the net present value, NPV.

01:03:09.110 --> 01:03:10.560
That's one answer.

01:03:10.560 --> 01:03:13.130
That was the correct
textbook answer.

01:03:13.130 --> 01:03:15.910
What's another answer of how do
I figure out the market value?

01:03:15.910 --> 01:03:16.790
AUDIENCE: Through the market.

01:03:16.790 --> 01:03:17.581
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

01:03:17.581 --> 01:03:18.450
Auction it off.

01:03:18.450 --> 01:03:21.230
How many people want to pay
me $1,000 for this today?

01:03:21.230 --> 01:03:22.630
No? $1,001?

01:03:22.630 --> 01:03:23.630
a thousand and whenever.

01:03:23.630 --> 01:03:25.430
We can auction it off
and figure out what

01:03:25.430 --> 01:03:27.300
the price is from the market.

01:03:27.300 --> 01:03:30.170
But in fact, what
we're doing by doing so

01:03:30.170 --> 01:03:31.760
is computing the present value.

01:03:31.760 --> 01:03:34.070
And the way we're doing
it is by figuring out

01:03:34.070 --> 01:03:38.450
what the price of a dollar
is in date one today.

01:03:38.450 --> 01:03:41.420
What the price of a dollar
in year two is today.

01:03:41.420 --> 01:03:44.420
And what the price of a
dollar is in year three today.

01:03:44.420 --> 01:03:46.760
Getting those exchange
rates and then

01:03:46.760 --> 01:03:51.710
converting all of those
different currencies to dollars

01:03:51.710 --> 01:03:52.531
today.

01:03:52.531 --> 01:03:53.030
Right?

01:03:53.030 --> 01:03:56.090
We know this we've
done this many times.

01:03:56.090 --> 01:04:05.400
So the way that you
figure out valuation

01:04:05.400 --> 01:04:11.590
is by using discount rates
that we get from the market

01:04:11.590 --> 01:04:14.200
and applying them to compute
present values, right?

01:04:14.200 --> 01:04:15.650
Very simple.

01:04:15.650 --> 01:04:19.420
So really, the components
of evaluation for bonds,

01:04:19.420 --> 01:04:22.130
if there's no uncertainty,
you already know.

01:04:22.130 --> 01:04:22.750
We've done it.

01:04:22.750 --> 01:04:24.610
That was last lecture.

01:04:24.610 --> 01:04:30.130
And for special cash flows like
annuities and perpetuities,

01:04:30.130 --> 01:04:32.350
we've got closed form solutions.

01:04:32.350 --> 01:04:35.944
Formulas, which you can program
up in Excel to figure out.

01:04:35.944 --> 01:04:37.360
The kind of risks
that we're going

01:04:37.360 --> 01:04:42.310
to focus on later on in this
lecture and in the lectures

01:04:42.310 --> 01:04:45.850
after we talk about
uncertainty is inflation risk.

01:04:45.850 --> 01:04:47.230
We talked about that, right?

01:04:47.230 --> 01:04:50.110
The fact that when you buy
a bond or you sell a bond,

01:04:50.110 --> 01:04:52.180
if the purchasing
power changes, that's

01:04:52.180 --> 01:04:55.840
going to introduce a
new kind of unknown

01:04:55.840 --> 01:04:57.460
that we need to grapple with.

01:04:57.460 --> 01:04:58.610
Credit risk.

01:04:58.610 --> 01:05:00.490
That's a major form
of risk that we're

01:05:00.490 --> 01:05:02.680
dealing with in
financial markets today

01:05:02.680 --> 01:05:05.380
and that we're likely to be
dealing with for years to come.

01:05:05.380 --> 01:05:10.100
You might like to borrow
from me or lend to me,

01:05:10.100 --> 01:05:12.500
