01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:17.900
to be around a year from
now, two years from now.

01:05:17.900 --> 01:05:20.960
Timing, which we'll come back
to a little bit later on.

01:05:20.960 --> 01:05:21.920
Liquidity.

01:05:21.920 --> 01:05:23.480
And then of course,
what currency.

01:05:23.480 --> 01:05:25.230
If we're doing
international borrowing,

01:05:25.230 --> 01:05:28.790
we have an extra dimension of
risk, which is fluctuations

01:05:28.790 --> 01:05:30.830
in the exchange rate, OK?

01:05:30.830 --> 01:05:33.980
So for the next
couple of lectures,

01:05:33.980 --> 01:05:37.760
I want to keep life simple and
talk just about riskless debt.

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:41.330
Riskless in terms of
default. So in particular I'm

01:05:41.330 --> 01:05:44.610
going to be talking about
US government bonds.

01:05:44.610 --> 01:05:45.380
All right?

01:05:45.380 --> 01:05:47.120
And I'll come back
to risky debt later.

01:05:47.120 --> 01:05:51.050
But for now, let's just focus
on the debt that will not

01:05:51.050 --> 01:05:54.500
default because you can always
print up dollars to pay off

01:05:54.500 --> 01:05:56.180
your creditors, right?

01:05:56.180 --> 01:05:57.800
Those dollars may
not be worth as much

01:05:57.800 --> 01:06:00.590
as you would like them to be
if you do too much of that,

01:06:00.590 --> 01:06:04.980
but for now, we're not
going to focus on default.

01:06:04.980 --> 01:06:08.980
OK so the first kind
of bond that we're

01:06:08.980 --> 01:06:13.870
going to try to price is what's
called a pure discount bond.

01:06:13.870 --> 01:06:16.780
This is a bond that is different
from a coupon bond in the sense

01:06:16.780 --> 01:06:18.190
that there are no coupons.

01:06:18.190 --> 01:06:23.530
So it only pays off
one payment at the end.

01:06:23.530 --> 01:06:25.410
And the reason it's
called the discount bond

01:06:25.410 --> 01:06:28.170
is because it is
what it sounds like--

01:06:28.170 --> 01:06:32.160
the price of the bond today
is going to be at a discount

01:06:32.160 --> 01:06:34.050
from the face value.

01:06:34.050 --> 01:06:37.980
If the face value is $1,000
and there's nothing in between,

01:06:37.980 --> 01:06:41.640
then the price of the banters
can't be greater than $1,000

01:06:41.640 --> 01:06:46.240
because money today is worth
more than money next year.

01:06:46.240 --> 01:06:49.410
So the price today is going
to be lower than $1,000.

01:06:49.410 --> 01:06:52.380
It's going to be a
discount over $1,000, hence

01:06:52.380 --> 01:06:54.150
the term pure discount bond.

01:06:54.150 --> 01:06:56.850
Now there are pure
discount bonds out there.

01:06:56.850 --> 01:07:00.120
US treasury bills
are examples, where

01:07:00.120 --> 01:07:03.450
there's one payoff at the
end and nothing in between.

01:07:03.450 --> 01:07:07.140
But awhile ago,
financial engineers

01:07:07.140 --> 01:07:08.994
came up with a rather
brilliant idea,

01:07:08.994 --> 01:07:11.160
which you may not think is
so brilliant because it's

01:07:11.160 --> 01:07:12.870
so painfully obvious.

01:07:12.870 --> 01:07:15.760
The government issues
coupon bonds as well.

01:07:15.760 --> 01:07:17.790
And typically, for
longer maturities,

01:07:17.790 --> 01:07:21.780
like five years,
15 and 30 years,

01:07:21.780 --> 01:07:25.980
there are no pure discount bonds
for those longer maturities.

01:07:25.980 --> 01:07:30.279
When the government issues them,
they issue them with coupons.

01:07:30.279 --> 01:07:31.820
But you can imagine
a situation where

01:07:31.820 --> 01:07:36.990
somebody would like to have
a discount bond for 30 years.

01:07:36.990 --> 01:07:38.910
And so some clever
financial engineer said,

01:07:38.910 --> 01:07:41.090
hey, here's what
I'm going to do.

01:07:41.090 --> 01:07:46.070
I'm going to buy up a lot of
these treasury coupon bonds

01:07:46.070 --> 01:07:50.480
and I'm going to issue
discount bonds that

01:07:50.480 --> 01:07:55.430
match exactly the coupon
payments from my treasury

01:07:55.430 --> 01:07:56.240
bonds.

01:07:56.240 --> 01:07:58.190
In other words, I'm
going to take the coupons

01:07:58.190 --> 01:08:03.840
and strip them and offer them
up as separate securities.

01:08:03.840 --> 01:08:08.070
And I'm going to
call these STRIPS.

01:08:08.070 --> 01:08:11.910
And these STRIPS, which
stands for separate trading

01:08:11.910 --> 01:08:15.600
of registered interest
and principal securities,

01:08:15.600 --> 01:08:20.100
created a huge market
for essentially

01:08:20.100 --> 01:08:23.040
what are government
bonds, but that

01:08:23.040 --> 01:08:26.790
have been pre-processed in
a relatively simple way.

01:08:26.790 --> 01:08:29.500
Now, this didn't
happen that long ago.

01:08:29.500 --> 01:08:32.550
Maybe, I don't know, 15 or 20
years ago they created STRIPS.

01:08:32.550 --> 01:08:35.146
So this is why I'm so excited
about financial markets

01:08:35.146 --> 01:08:37.520
and why I think all of you
have tremendous opportunities.

01:08:37.520 --> 01:08:40.500
It's because there
are so many ideas that

01:08:40.500 --> 01:08:44.640
may seem obvious to you but
are not obvious to the market.

01:08:44.640 --> 01:08:47.910
And there's no
patent on good ideas.

01:08:47.910 --> 01:08:49.830
There's no monopoly
on good ideas.

01:08:49.830 --> 01:08:52.920
You can actually
create tremendous value

01:08:52.920 --> 01:08:54.660
by coming up with
what you might think

01:08:54.660 --> 01:08:56.970
of as so simple a
solution but that

01:08:56.970 --> 01:09:01.220
solves problems for very
large financial institutions.

01:09:01.220 --> 01:09:02.630
Now how do we
price these things.

01:09:02.630 --> 01:09:05.569
Well, this is just a one liner.

01:09:05.569 --> 01:09:08.600
The price of a
discount on is simply

01:09:08.600 --> 01:09:11.270
equal to its face
value discounted

01:09:11.270 --> 01:09:15.529
to the present by the
appropriate interest rate.

01:09:15.529 --> 01:09:16.670
That's it.

01:09:16.670 --> 01:09:17.740
Pure and simple.

01:09:17.740 --> 01:09:21.430
We're now done with pricing
pure discount bonds.

01:09:21.430 --> 01:09:23.800
There's nothing else to it.

01:09:23.800 --> 01:09:25.720
OK.

01:09:25.720 --> 01:09:29.290
It turns out that this is a
really wonderful relationship

01:09:29.290 --> 01:09:32.830
because if you've got two
of these three variables

01:09:32.830 --> 01:09:36.189
in this equation,
you've got the third.

01:09:36.189 --> 01:09:38.260
If I tell you what
the face value is

01:09:38.260 --> 01:09:40.580
and what the interest rate
is, you've got the price.

01:09:40.580 --> 01:09:43.122
If I tell you what the price
is and what the face value is,

01:09:43.122 --> 01:09:44.330
you've got the interest rate.

01:09:44.330 --> 01:09:46.960
And if I give you the
interest rate of the price,

01:09:46.960 --> 01:09:50.229
you can actually figure out what
the face value is, all right?

01:09:50.229 --> 01:09:52.779
So this relationship is
going to be very handy when

01:09:52.779 --> 01:09:55.150
we look at the prices
of these instruments

01:09:55.150 --> 01:09:59.710
and we want to now infer
what that says about what's

01:09:59.710 --> 01:10:01.420
going on with interest rates.

01:10:01.420 --> 01:10:04.150
In fact, what I'm going to
show you next time is that when

01:10:04.150 --> 01:10:06.190
we look at the
newspaper and we take

01:10:06.190 --> 01:10:10.210
a look at the prices of
discounted coupon bonds,

01:10:10.210 --> 01:10:14.755
implicit in those prices is
a forecast of the future.

01:10:14.755 --> 01:10:16.380
This is as close as
any of you are ever

01:10:16.380 --> 01:10:18.270
